English Life of Christ spiritual narrative with scientific commentary, quoting texts from Newton, describing his qualities and communications with God;

The sentence structure "But that Day we did consent, that we might not agree" mirrors earlier context about the heart's purification eliminating evil intentions, implying the clause continues explaining his interaction with Heaven versus earthly desire versus the will of God.

Final token "consent" ends mid-clause ("But we consent"), part of a paired contrast ("But we then renounce..."), strongly expecting "ed our thoughts" or "ed the things within us" or "ed with our records," completing the explanation that he rejected wickedness and held differing beliefs.
